hamsterpopcorn [info] Thinking back, I believe my symptoms started my first year in college. Often times narcolepsy can be brought on by the flu, which is what I believe happened to me. At 18 years old about 2 weeks into my first quarter in college I came down with a really bad case of the flu and thinking back that is when my symptoms started. 1. First symptoms: Suddenly I was falling asleep in class every single day. I tried getting more sleep at night, but it continued to happen. I would fall asleep sitting up and sometimes I would lean forward to try and pay closer attention but my eyes would close and I would be awake but I wouldn’t be able to open them again. It was always the same class around 4pm. My friends would make fun of me because I couldn’t stay awake through a single movie or for more than one or two episodes of a TV show or sometimes I would fall asleep mid-conversation and they would slam books next to me or slap my forehead and laugh because I would try to open my eyes again but couldn’t.2. Gradually or suddenly: How do I say this? It was new, like something that I hadn’t done before, but there were so many other changes in my life while transitioning to college I thought it was associated with those changes. I would say it gradually worsened and concerned me more. At first I was falling asleep every day at 4pm, but then as time progressed it was 2 hours after waking up as well as 4pm and I needed those two naps every day, more if I was short any sleep from the night before. It got to a point where doing simple tasks like putting laundry away or playing with my dog suddenly my body would get really heavy and I would lay down on the floor and sleep for about an hour, especially if this was around 4pm or 2 hours after waking up. I scared my roommates because I would slump over the table while eating breakfast. 3. When I decided to seek help: I was already going from doctor to doctor, but I was diagnosed with depression and anxiety, then bipolar disorder and ADHD. Turns out these kind of mood symptoms are commonly caused by narcolepsy, but my doctors assumed my sleepiness was a result of having these mood disorders. No matter what medication I took, the sleepiness would not go away and the depression, anxiety, and lack of focus continued. I gained about 30 pounds from the inactivity, my grades took a deep dive, my social life was dying because I had no energy to go out with friends, and I didn’t even have the energy to take care of myself or clean up my house because I would fall asleep all the time. I had many breakdowns about it and when I finally did go to a doctor seeking answers about this daytime sleepiness, between having to wait for appointments to see my doctors and waiting for insurance to approve things, I was finally diagnosed after 10 months of actively seeking this diagnosis (go to my comments and see one I wrote about an MSLT if you want more details about the diagnosing process). I suffered with narcolepsy for about 3 years before being put on the right medication. It really has changed my quality of life and now even though I experience some tiredness during the day (around 4pm and 2 hours after waking up, of course) I am able to actually fight off sleep and power through, which is something I didn’t even know was possible. I’m looking to lose the weight, get my grades back on track, and finally rebuild my life from the destruction that the mood symptoms caused. It hasn’t been easy and it seemed to come out of left field, but I am relieved there is treatment for what most people don’t realize is a debilitating condition.(Sorry this is long I know, hope I helped :P)
