MagpieMelon [info] I agree with you. I also believe that anxiety and depression are symptoms of something being wrong, whether it’s lifestyle or a physical problem, and not just something that people have. I have had anxiety my whole life, I was diagnosed with depression at 21 but had been battling it since 14. I was just very good at hiding it. I was suicidal at 16, and then again at 21. Doctors only ever told me I had depression/was anxious but never gave me a reason why. They tested me for various things and never found anything wrong. It was only when I found out I had celiac disease at 21 that things got better. I’m not saying it was a magical cure, since I still have days where I’m depressed, and I still get anxious. But it’s at a normal level, and is perfectly manageable. It is normal to feel anxious/depressed, what’s not normal is it taking over your life which is what happened to me. People telling me that depression and anxiety were just what I had could have made me stop looking for an answer. And believe me I did want to give up when I was told that this was how it was and antidepressants and therapy were my only options. I went to therapy and I was told o didn’t need to be there because I had no issues that needed fixing, except for undiagnosed celiac disease. I think normalising it to the degree that it has been is very dangerous. It’s not normal to be too scared to pick up a phone or order some food, it’s a sign of something being very wrong. I used to walk into a job that I loved and was very good at, and have a panic attack and be sent home almost everyday. But that stopped once I figured out the problem. It was still hard to go in, and I did still get nervous, but I was able to get through it once I found the problem.
