ooga_booga_booger [info] Make sure to get documentation of your illness ASAP and get in contact with the center of disabilities with your school if you feel like you'll need accommodations. It's a lot of hoops to jump through but worth it (if you need it)! I personally did not get accommodations but instead went through extensive CBT and it's starting to be manageable. GET A THERAPIST ASAP! (S)he will help you so much and will help you figure out if you need accommodations or not. From a personal experience, I have been diagnosed with depression, anxiety, PTSD, anorexia, and chemical dependency. I went from dropping out of school as an undergrad to undergo rehab and various mental outpatient facilities to getting into four grad schools! You can do it! I am almost certain that you will not be the only one with a mental illness when you're in grad school (a fellow peer of mine also has PTSD). If you choose to talk to your professor about your mental illness, make sure to emphasize how your mental illness can make learning more difficult and ask if they have any advice or additional reading to help bolster your learning. All of my profs have been super understandable as long as they know that you've been doing what you can to keep up with the material. Because i struggled with mental illness, my grades suffered for a year or so, so be sure to mention that in your statement of purpose. I told them how I knew I fucked up but instead of running away, I did what I could to fix my mistakes and move forward. I even called a few schools asking for an interview because what was on the papers (i.e., transcripts) did not accurately reflect on my skills as a potential graduate student. Keep in mind your professors are people too!  Please do NOT think that you are inadequate for grad school just because your brain is wired differently from others. We are all different. You have just as much to contribute to a graduate program as anyone else. Your diagnosis does not define you as a student; your knowledge and desire to learn more will define you as a grad student. If you have any more questions, please PM me. I was in your shoes a year ago and felt beyond discouraged about my future due to my mental illnesses. You CAN do it. I promise. If you don't have a support system, then know you at least have some rando on reddit behind your back 1000%. You might have to put in a bit more work, but it will be BEYOND rewarding. Trust me on that. You totally got this; I have faith in you! :)
