lonelygalaxy_TA [info] You might be treated differently you might not. It depends on the person.For example I was diagnosed with depression, add and anxiety at 14. My mom understood, the rest of my family not so much. However my mom studied Psychology in college so that might be one reason.Its important to have someone to talk to/support you. Mental health is hard but its worse dealing with it alone. If your the mild mannered type then having someone you trust advocate for you is also helpful. Sometimes people like to walk over people with mental illnesses so having an advocate is great.Also its important to take your antidepressants as prescribed. It'll takes a month or so to see if it actually works or if you need to switch to something else. Missing a dose isnt good but if you're the type whose not good with pills/bad memory then talk with your doctor. When i first started I had a hard time remembering to take my pills consistently so my mom had to talk to my doctor about lowering the dosage until i got on a routine. Side effects can be bad for some people but the worst I ever had on antidepressants was change in appetite.Be strong and be educated. The future is brighter then the present. *hugs*
