inattentiveexecutive [info] I'll go first, with some of my background story.As a kid, I was very disorganized, with  time and in my space, and in school a common thread was that I was  brilliant but that I often got lost in the middle of an exercise  (specially in maths). I was not hyperactive, but I did have a tendency  to daydream and get very distracted in class. My dad's mantra was "if  only you applied yourself a little bit..."During  uni, I had a crisis. I went to the psychologist because I felt  frustrated. I knew I had talents and people kept telling me that I was  very intelligent, but I was incapable of applying myself to something. I  felt like a revved up engine that is not connected to any wheels, with a  lot of potential and little outcome. I was diagnosed with depression,  more specifically with cyclothymia which is a mild type of bipolar  disorder. To be fair, I was indeed depressed, but I always felt like the  depression was an outcome and I wanted to go for the root whatever it  was. I just felt trapped, limited, with a lot of things that I could do,  a lot of things I wanted to do, but with no ability to execute or not  having the opportunities to do so.That  was almost 20 years ago, an it took me about 10 years to overcome my  depression because I declined taking any medication. I was functionally  depressed, I learned to ride the low and high tides of cyclothymia, so I  focused (heh) on understanding myself better, understanding the world,  and figuring out how to cope with my  brain, however it was wired.Nowadays,  and mostly throughout my life in some way or another, I have trouble  following through with anything. I'm much more organized than I ever  was, but my systems break catastrophically once or twice a year,  throwing me into an existential crisis. I have no trouble finding a job,  but I cannot keep one for more than 6 months. My record was 2 years on  the job (on my first job!), but it was a huge drama for the people I was  working with, with constant depression episodes, anxiety issues,  migraines, etc. I've never been fired, but after 6 months I get bored  and start seeing problems everywhere, or just think I need to switch  careers because I really don't like what I'm doing (only to come back to  it a couple of cycles later).I love  reading, but I have trouble reading and I'm a very slow reader. With  non-fiction and academic writing (I tried to follow the academic path) I  have the problem that as I'm reading some article or book, when I'm  just two paragraphs in, my brain starts firing up all sorts of ideas,  finding connections everywhere, and asking me to go deeper into  something or other and just ignoring the piece I'm currently reading.  Obviously, I had to drop out from the academic path because I got  trapped in rabbit hole after rabbit hole and going nowhere. It's still  the most stimulating thing in this world for me, I just have a hard time  staying focused.Living in my head is  just a constant chatter, from morning till night. There is always a  constant thread (more like threads, plural) going on, always coming up  with new ideas. I mostly live up there, even if I'm doing something in  the physical world. In contrast to other people with ADD, I can keep up  with most threads in my head, although I struggle coming down to one of  them. So I can be having a conversation with someone while thinking of  the depths of the universe, and when called on that I have difficulty  remembering exactly what that person told me, but I can remember it  after a minute.I'm a polymath. I'm an  engineer who has also studied social sciences, philosophy, music, design  and many other things. Not out of choice, but because I can't stay in  one area long enough. Engineering is my main skill, the only one I  manage to stick for long. The rest I struggle because I really want to  pursue them, but I cannot fit everything in my life. So I go through  lots of phases where I'm deeply obsessed with something, create plans  for mastery, and then drop it for the next thing. I want to learn  everything, and I want to learn it now.The  worst is that I often feel restless. I might not have to do anything  but my head is asking for action. Sometimes it's cool, it pushes me to  do things and I've achieved a lot of personal goals because of that  drive. But more often I feel paralyzed, wanting to do so many things  that I cannot do just one. Or start doing one only to be attracted to  something else, and then something else. In the worst episodes, it's a  total paralysis and some sort of frustration or anguish, a feeling of  being pulled in all directions at once. I sometimes wake up in the  middle of the night with this feeling, or I'm unable to fall asleep in  the first place.
